That styling plan is perfect. For Typora or any Markdown viewer that accepts CSS, you can set up a minimal theme that matches your palette and font pairing. Here’s a short, accessible CSS block you can drop into a file such as `guided_support.css` and reference on export:

```css
:root {
  --accent-blue: #6FA9C7;
  --accent-sage: #9FB69F;
  --accent-gray: #BEB9B5;
  --font-serif: "Noto Serif", Georgia, serif;
  --font-sans: "Source Sans Pro", "Noto Sans", sans-serif;
}

html {
  font-size: 16px;
  color: #000;
  background-color: #fff;
}

body {
  font-family: var(--font-serif);
  line-height: 1.6;
  margin: 1in;
}

h1, h2, h3 {
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  color: var(--accent-blue);
  margin-top: 1.5em;
  margin-bottom: 0.5em;
}

code, pre {
  background-color: #f5f5f5;
  border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-gray);
  padding-left: 0.5em;
}

table {
  border-collapse: collapse;
  width: 100%;
}

th, td {
  border: 1px solid var(--accent-gray);
  padding: 0.4em;
}

a {
  color: var(--accent-blue);
  text-decoration: none;
}

a:hover, a:focus {
  text-decoration: underline;
}

footer {
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  font-size: 0.8em;
  color: var(--accent-gray);
  text-align: center;
  margin-top: 2em;
}

/* Accessibility adjustments */
@media print {
  body {
    color: #000;
    background: #fff;
  }
  a {
    color: #000;
  }
}
```

Attach the style when you export:  
```bash
pandoc guide.md -o Guided_Support_Conversation.pdf --css guided_support.css
```

This keeps the soft accent colors if viewed on‑screen but remains clear and readable when printed in black‑and‑white. 

