Sure thing — if you’d like it to feel visually “finished” whether someone prints it or scrolls through it, you can add a few gentle dividers and spacing tweaks to your stylesheet. They create breathing room without relying on heavy color.

Here’s an extension you can append to your CSS block:

```css
/* ---- Visual dividers and rhythm ---- */

/* Horizontal rules between major sections */
hr {
  border: none;
  border-top: 2px solid var(--accent-sage);
  margin: 2em 0;
}

/* Extra spacing after tables and code blocks */
table + p,
pre + p,
blockquote + p {
  margin-top: 1em;
}

/* Blockquote prompts look like reflection boxes */
blockquote {
  border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-blue);
  background-color: #fafafa;
  padding: 0.75em 1em;
  margin: 1em 0;
  font-style: italic;
}

blockquote::before {
  content: "✏️ ";
  color: var(--accent-sage);
  font-style: normal;
}

/* Section dividers (headers to content) */
h1 + p,
h2 + p {
  margin-top: 0.25em;
}

/* Ensure enough whitespace at page breaks in print */
@page {
  margin: 1in;
}

@media print {
  hr {
    border-top: 1px solid #aaa;
  }
  blockquote {
    border-color: #999;
    background: #fff;
  }
}

/* ---- End of dividers & spacing ---- */
```

These rules do a few things:  
* **`hr` lines** give a soft separation between “steps” or topic blocks.  
* **Blockquotes** where you place reflection prompts get a subtle box so users can spot writing areas quickly.  
* Spacing rules prevent content from feeling cramped or merging when printed.  

When you merge everything with Pandoc or view in Typora, these cues help each section read like its own breathing space without turning the worksheet into formal clinical paperwork.

